    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="poem">
                <head>Lines to Margaret</head>
                <lg>
                    <l>Within the dark forest with pines overspread</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">Lies a valley retired and fair,</l>
                    <l>The branches that form a green arch overhead,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">Scarce suffer the sun’s entrance there.</l>
                    <l>In the middle there standeth a moss grown cell</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">A streamlet runs murmuring nigh,</l>
                    <l>And here, as they say, used the fairies to dwell,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">In the merry old days gone by.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                     <l>And near to the cell, with full many a rose,</l>
                     <l rend="indent(2)">And many a woodbine entwined,</l>
                     <l>Stands a cottage in tranquil and soft repose—</l>
                     <l rend="indent(2)">With the deep dark forest behind;</l>
                     <l>In the front is a glade of the softest green,</l>
                     <l rend="indent(2)">Where Pixies and Fairies had met;</l>
                     <l>Nor ever a Fairy could equal I ween,</l>
                     <l rend="indent(2)">The beautiful queen of the vale—Margaret.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                    <l>Her form, in its beauty and innocence bright,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">Bonnded light as the spirit within,</l>
                    <l>While from her dark eyes shone a full dear delight—</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">All hearts and all spirits to win.</l>
                    <l>So softly she spoke and so sweetly she smil'd,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">Her favored companions to greet—</l>
                    <l>Her voice—as the note of the turtle dove—mild,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">Her smile—as the rosebud—was sweet.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                    <l>Dark and rich were her locks, of the auburn hue,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">In the breeze as they floated down;</l>
                    <l>Fair and clear was her face, as the sunlight, true,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">And her eyes, as the hazel, brown,</l>
                    <l>Which ever would smile and look down upon me,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">With a fond long look of regret,</l>
                    <l>As I wandered on in this woodland so free,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">With the beautiful queen of the vale—Margaret.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                    <l>We sat in the cell where the Fairies had play’d,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">And would answer the bird’s merry song,</l>
                    <l>Or list to the music the tiny waves made,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">As the streamlet ran prattling along.</l>
                    <l>While her joyous voice in low accents would ring.</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">In the grove all sweet and all clear.</l>
                    <l>Oft causing in haste and in terror to spring,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">The stag from his covert near.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                    <l>When the rays of the morn fell so softly around,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">And the trees in the light wind flung,</l>
                    <l>Their quivering shade on the bright chequered ground,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">While among them the nightingale sung—</l>
                    <l>When mid the green grass at the first peep of dawn,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">The dew drops like diamonds were set,</l>
                    <l>Then oft have I strolled on that shadowy lawn</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">With the beautiful queen of the vale—Margaret.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                    <l>Alas! for no longer those accents I hear,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">No longer those smiles fall on me;</l>
                    <l>That form and that spirit so loving and dear,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">Are things but of sad memory.</l>
                    <l>The dark forest grows and the streamlet runs on,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">The cell aud the cottage remain,</l>
                    <l>But the light and the pride of the valley is gone,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">And the valley is desert again.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                    <l>The birds sweetest notes meet no sweeter response;</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">The stag slumbers on in his lair;</l>
                    <l>The branches and thistles are growing where once</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">Bloomed her roses so lovely and fair.</l>
                    <l>Nor time nor long absence can ever efface,</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">Nor can my heart ever forget,</l>
                    <l>The swift flitting form or the pure simple grace</l>
                    <l rend="indent(2)">Of the beautiful queen of the vale—Margaret</l>
                </lg>
            </div>
